The Romans, however, gave one, and only one, sound to any vowel. The Latin a, ior instance, had always the sound oi the English a in ,tethea But this one sound oi a vowel they made in two ways: either protracting it, thus making it long, or clipping it off, thus making it short. This distinction as to the length oi time taken in sounding a vowel they called quantity.

The quantity oi a vowel, then, is the relative time taken in sounding it.

With reference to quantity,vowels are either long or short A long vowel should take twice the time oi a short vowel.

In printing, quantity is indicated hy a mark over the vowel ; eg. long a is printed d, and short a, ἄ. A vowel which may be either long or short is called common, and hae both marks; ep. ἔ.
